    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "In the upcoming Men's Winter Olympics Hockey game, scheduled for 2026-02-21:\nIf Slovakia win, the market will resolve to \"Slovakia\".\nIf Finland win, the market will resolve to \"Finland\".\nIf the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.\nIf the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.\nThe result will be determined based on the final score including any overtime periods and shootouts. In the event of a shootout, one goal will be added to the winning team's score for the purpose of resolution.",
    "outcome": "Finland",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nFinland secured the bronze medal in the Men's ice hockey tournament at the 2026 Winter Olympics by defeating Slovakia 6-1. Driven by a determination to bounce back from a heartbreaking semi-final loss to Canada where they squandered a 2-0 lead, the Finnish team demonstrated formidable offensive power and defensive resilience. Key contributions from Erik Haula, Joel Armia, and goaltender Juuse Saros allowed Finland to dominate the third period, scoring four unanswered goals to seal the decisive victory over Slovakia.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2026-02-21 1st Period (07:27):** Sebastian Aho opens the scoring for Finland, poking in a loose puck to give them a 1-0 lead [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n- **2026-02-21 2nd Period (08:05/28:05):** Erik Haula scores his first goal of the game with a wrist shot, extending Finland's lead to 2-0 [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n- **2026-02-21 2nd Period (19:30/39:30):** Tomas Tatar scores for Slovakia with a backhand shot after a fortuitous bounce, cutting the deficit to 2-1 just before the intermission [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n- **2026-02-21 3rd Period (08:27/48:27):** Roope Hintz scores a crucial power-play goal, deflecting a shot from Miro Heiskanen to make it 3-1 for Finland [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n- **2026-02-21 3rd Period (09:09/49:09):** Kaapo Kakko scores just 42 seconds after Hintz, increasing the lead to 4-1 and effectively putting the game out of reach [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n- **2026-02-21 3rd Period (15:32/55:32):** Joel Armia scores an empty-net goal to make it 5-1 [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n- **2026-02-21 3rd Period (18:42/58:42):** Erik Haula adds a second empty-net goal to finalize the score at 6-1 [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad].\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe root cause of Finland's dominant performance was their intense motivation to rebound from a painful semi-final defeat against Canada, where they lost a 2-0 lead late in the game. This psychological factor caused a highly focused and aggressive approach in the bronze medal game against Slovakia. This approach led to an early 2-0 advantage established by goals from Sebastian Aho and Erik Haula [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]. While Slovakia briefly gained momentum with a late second-period goal by Tomas Tatar, this triggered a concerted response from Finland in the locker room, determined not to repeat their semi-final collapse. The proximate triggers for the blowout were early third-period penalties taken by Slovakia, which Finland capitalized on with a power-play goal by Roope Hintz, rapidly followed by an even-strength goal by Kaapo Kakko [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]. These rapid-fire goals broke Slovakia's resistance and resulted in a decisive 6-1 final outcome.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nSlovakia pushed back effectively towards the end of the second period, demonstrating resilience. Their late goal by Tomas Tatar to make it 2-1 gave them significant momentum heading into the final frame. Furthermore, Slovakia had previously defeated Finland 4-1 in the preliminary round, suggesting they had the tactical capability to overcome the Finnish team [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]. However, this momentum was overwhelmed by Finland's disciplined third-period execution and Slovakia's costly penalties, which halted any potential comeback.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: Sebastian Aho scores opening goal for Finland\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters: Established early dominance and set the tone for Finland's offensive pressure.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]\n- E2: Erik Haula scores to make it 2-0\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters: Provided a crucial cushion for Finland.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]\n- E3: Tomas Tatar scores to cut lead to 2-1\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters: Gave Slovakia temporary momentum and threatened Finland's lead.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]\n- E4: Roope Hintz scores power-play goal in 3rd period\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters: Broke Slovakia's momentum and restored a comfortable two-goal lead.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]\n- E5: Kaapo Kakko scores to make it 4-1\n  - Date: 2026-02-21\n  - Why it matters: Functionally ended the competitive phase of the game.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Finland wins 6-1 | [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad] | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Final score confirmed across multiple sources. |\n| Aho and Haula score to give Finland 2-0 lead | [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad] | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Detail on first and second period goals. |\n| Tatar scores to make it 2-1 | [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad] | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Late second period momentum shift. |\n| Finland scores four in the 3rd period | [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad] | 2026-02-21 | 1.0 | Hintz, Kakko, Armia, and Haula goals detailed. |\n| Finland motivated by semi-final loss | [art_sports_20260221_007_b974e4ad], [art_sports_20260221_005_c503e667] | 2026-02-21 | 0.9 | Player quotes confirming this psychological factor. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe primary alternative path hinged on the start of the third period. If Slovakia had capitalized on their late second-period momentum and scored an equalizing goal early in the third, instead of taking penalties, the game could have remained highly competitive and potentially favored the team with ascending momentum. Finland's psychological state was fragile after blowing a 2-0 lead the previous day, and an equalizer might have triggered a similar collapse.\n",
