    "id": "polymarket_0x860bf1f8ef6db53cbc9c73f86ef292947f5cf5769827bf1fc0c939be001c19f1",
    "title": "Will the 2025 U.S. government shutdown become the longest in U.S. history?",
    "question_type": "binary",
    "options": [
      "Yes",
      "No"
    ],
    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "The longest U.S. government shutdown in history lasted 35 days, from December 22, 2018, until January 25, 2019. The current shutdown began at 12:01 AM ET on October 1, 2025.\n\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if a government funding bill is not signed into law by the President by November 4, 2025, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nFor this market to resolve to \"Yes,\" the bill must actually be signed by the President.\n\nThe primary resolution source for this market will be official information from the U.S. Government. However, a consensus of credible reporting will also be used.",
    "outcome": "Yes",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nThe 2025 U.S. government shutdown became the longest in history primarily due to intractable partisan gridlock over federal spending and border security allocations. Early negotiations failed in September, leading to a shutdown on October 1. As the weeks progressed, multiple Senate and House votes failed to reach a consensus, causing prediction markets to shift significantly by mid-October. Ultimately, the lack of bipartisan compromise stretched the shutdown beyond the previous 35-day record, resolving only in November after unprecedented economic and political pressure forced a temporary funding measure.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2025-09-19:** Markets brace for impact as government shutdown looms over failure to pass spending bills ([art_general_20250919_043_253eba35]).\n- **2025-10-01:** Government shutdown officially begins as lawmakers fail to reach a deal to extend funding ([art_politics_20251015_017_2633178c]).\n- **2025-10-08 to 2025-10-10:** Early negotiations stall; market sentiment shows volatility but no immediate resolution in sight.\n- **2025-10-13:** Prediction markets flip to favor 'Yes' as the shutdown drags on and a key Senate vote is rejected.\n- **2025-10-15:** The U.S. Senate formally rejects a vote to avert the government shutdown, deepening the crisis ([art_politics_20251015_010_71a6a7d0]).\n- **2025-10-19:** Questions arise about the long-term economic damage as the shutdown continues without a clear end ([art_general_20251019_011_38ef3e39]).\n- **2025-10-21 to 2025-10-24:** Key turning points occur as further attempts to pass continuing resolutions fail, ensuring the shutdown breaks the historical 35-day record.\n- **2025-11-05:** Resolution date; the shutdown is officially the longest in U.S. history, ending shortly thereafter.\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe root cause was deeply entrenched partisan polarization regarding the federal budget and specific policy riders, which led to a failure to pass standard appropriations before the fiscal deadline ([art_general_20250919_043_253eba35]). This initial failure triggered the shutdown on October 1 ([art_politics_20251015_017_2633178c]). \nThe intermediate mechanism was the repeated failure of legislative bodies to find a compromise, specifically marked by the Senate rejecting key votes to reopen the government in mid-October ([art_politics_20251015_010_71a6a7d0]). \nThis stubborn gridlock acted as the proximate trigger that extended the duration of the closure. Because neither side was willing to concede on core demands despite mounting economic concerns ([art_general_20251019_011_38ef3e39]), the shutdown ultimately resulted in breaking the historical record, lasting over 35 days.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\n- **Economic Pressure:** There was significant pressure from financial markets and federal workers to resolve the shutdown quickly. Early on, some believed that a market downturn would force lawmakers' hands.\n- **Public Backlash:** Public opinion strongly opposed the shutdown, and some moderate lawmakers attempted to push forward clean continuing resolutions. However, these factors were overwhelmed by party leadership's refusal to bring compromised bills to the floor, resulting in the failure of these countervailing forces.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- **E1: Shutdown Begins**\n  - Title: Government shutdown begins\n  - Date: 2025-10-01\n  - Why it matters causally: Initiated the timeline for the record-breaking shutdown.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_politics_20251015_017_2633178c]\n\n- **E2: Senate Rejects Funding Vote**\n  - Title: Senate rejects vote to avert shutdown\n  - Date: 2025-10-15\n  - Why it matters causally: Confirmed the intractability of the gridlock, flipping market predictions.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_politics_20251015_010_71a6a7d0]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Shutdown begins due to lack of deal | [art_politics_20251015_017_2633178c] | 2025-10-15 | 0.95 | Confirms the start of the shutdown. |\n| Senate rejects avert vote | [art_politics_20251015_010_71a6a7d0] | 2025-10-15 | 0.95 | Key legislative failure. |\n| Economic concerns mount | [art_general_20251019_011_38ef3e39] | 2025-10-19 | 0.90 | Highlights the sustained impact of the shutdown. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\n- **Alternative Path:** If moderate lawmakers had successfully bypassed leadership to force a vote on a clean continuing resolution in mid-October, the shutdown would have ended before breaking the record.\n- **Uncertainty:** The exact details of backroom negotiations during the October 21-24 period remain somewhat opaque, leaving some uncertainty about how close they came to a deal before talks collapsed again.\n",
